Conceptual¶

Q: Explain the differences between bagging and boosting and explain how machine learning methods in general use these strategies to build robust models using tree models?

Both are ensamble techniques. In bagging we select bootstrap datasets from the training data and fit one tree for each boostrap dataset. Hence, all trees can be fitted in parralel. To make predictions, all fitted trees are used to make a prediction about the new data. After that, these predictions of all trees were aggregated, by the calculation of a mean (regression) or the selection the mode (classification) as the final prediction.

In boosting, we build the trees sequentially, because each tree depends on his predecessor. This dependency comes from the fact, that each subsequent tree is fitted by the residuals of his predecessor. However, each subsequent tree comes with a different weight, when it comes the prediction, which is also different to bagging.

As I said, both techniques result in an ensamle of models to make predictions. Im machine learning this is used to create a better model/ensamble that fits the response better than each model individually. This way one can reduce errors caused by a high variance each individual model could have.

Q: What are the main differences between Random Forests and AdaBoost regarding how the base learners are trained, how samples are weighted, how predictions are made and how robust are they regarding overfitting?

The main idea of the learning is quite different in random forest (RF) and AdaBoost (AB), which is just a special boosting algorithm. In RF all trees are trained on a subset of predictors and a subset of the training data (bootstap datasets). Additionally, all trees and training data points are equally weighted. In AB, each tree is trained on all predictors and with all (and the same) predictor values coming from the training data. However, during training the weights of the training data points change from tree to tree. The weights used for the training data points of a tree are calulated on the error of the predecesssing tree for each data point. This way, the missclassified responses of the previous tree are more important in the subsequent tree. Additionally, each tree comes with a different trust factor, which also depends on the error of the tree calculated on the weighted training data used for the training of that particular tree. These trust factors are relevant, when it comes to making predictions.

Predictions are made slightly different in both of the techniques, i.e. RF and AB. In RF predictions are made on a majority vote (taking the mode) of all trees. In AB the trust factor is relevant for making predictions. Like in RF all trees are supposed to predict an outcome based on the new data. After that the outcomes are weighted based on the trust factors of the tree, before it come to a majority vote. However, RF prevents overfitting more than AB, since AB make use of the weighting training data points based on the model itself. Additionally, it comes with a trust factor for each tree, which is also calulated on the model and traing data. This way it is more related to the training data than RF. Moreover, RF make use of different predictors and different training data (boostrap datasets) in the trees, which reduces the variance much more than the boosting itself could ever do. So in the end, AB/boosting comes with more parameters within the model (i.e. trust factor and weights) than RF. In general, more parameters comes with more flexibility but are less robust against overfitting.

I: Interprete the results¶

Here, I trained a 'perfect' tree (MSE = 0.0) according to the training data. In the examples from the assignment instructions this is not the case. I assume, that a different maximum tree size was used during training. Even if my decision tree is perfect in accuracy, it is a way more complicated that the one in the material. It is even too big to plot it in proper dimensions here in the notebook. So this way I didn't benefit from the main advantage of tree based models, i.e. the high interpretability.

Anyway, the metric of accuracy/missclassification used here is irrelevant for the estimation of the models error, since I tested it against the data used for training.

plt.plot(sizes, results['mean_test_score'].apply(lambda s : 1-s), marker="o")
plt.xlabel('size')
plt.ylabel('error rate')
plt.show()

I: Interprete the results.¶

Looking at the diagrams, it seems to be possible to reduce the size of the tree by pruning and came up with a quite good model with an accuracy of 75%. In my case I would choose a max tree size of 13.

I: Interprete the results¶

The prunes tree performs much better on the test data, which indicatess, that it is a much better model for the prediction absed on new data (accuracy: 73.5%). Additionally, the pruned model with max tree size 13 is much smaller than the original one. Hence, it is much easier to interpret this tree, proofed by the poltting

The comparison between the two pruned trees shos, that the model comes with much lower variance, when considering a smaller size. This is shown by a comparison of the accuracies/missclassifications of the models (73.5% vs. 72.5%). And once again, a smaller size results in a much better understandable tree.

I: Interprete the results¶

The trained bagging model with 500 trees performes very good on the training data, since it comes with a MSE of 1.98. However, testing it aginst unseen data, it is not that good, since it comes with a MSE of 11.6. But we also have to consider, that this model consists of 500 tree, which is very complex.

The second baging model trained with 25 trees is much smaller. However, it comes with just a little decrease in accuracy, since we could measure a MSE of approx. 12 against the test data.
